{"title_page": "Midrasha", "text_new": "A '''''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}''''' ([[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]: {{hebrew|\u05de\u05d3\u05e8\u05e9\u05d4}}, pl. ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot/midrashas}}'') is an institute of [[Torah study]] for women, generally in [[Israel]], and roughly the equivalent of a [[yeshiva]] for men. \nAn alternative term, and translation, is '[[seminary]]' ({{hebrew|\u05e1\u05de\u05d9\u05e0\u05e8}}); <ref name=\"science.co.il\">[https://www.science.co.il/jewish-studies/Midrashot.php ''Midrashot''], science.co.il</ref> these are modeled on the [[Sarah_Schenirer#Teacher's_Seminary|institution established by Sarah Schenirer]] in 1923.\n\"''Midrasha''\" is often associated with Religious Zionist institutions, while \"Seminary\" refers to ''[[Haredi]]'' institutions.\nA ''midrasha'' that offers [[academic degree|degree studies]] is sometimes called a ''machon'' ({{hebrew|\u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df}}, institute).\n\nThe word \"''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}''\" is based on the term ''[[beit midrash]]'', \"house of study\".  It is [[cognate]] with the [[Arabic]] \"''{{transl|ar|[[madrasa|madrasah]]}}'',\" which also refers to a place of learning.\n\nThe term ''Midrasha'' is sometimes used  more widely, referring to [[Cultural Judaism|pluralistic]], as opposed to [[orthodox Judaism|orthodox]], educational  institutions.\nIt may also refer to [[field school]]s that organize seminars and nature field trips.<ref name=\"science.co.il\"/>\n\n==Structure==\n===Curriculum===\n''{{lang|he-Latn|Midrashot}}'' and seminaries vary in curriculum and [[Orthodox Judaism#Social and philosophic differences|philosophy]]. \n<ref name=\"Lilith\">[https://www.lilith.org/blog/2014/09/a-modest-year-in-israel-when-young-women-go-to-seminary/ A Modest Year in Israel: When Young Women go to \u201cSeminary\u201d]. [[Lilith (magazine)|''Lilith'']], 2014 </ref>\nAll cover [[Tanakh]] (Hebrew Bible), [[Jewish philosophy]], [[Halacha|Jewish law]]  and [[Musar Literature|Musar (Ethics)]] / [[Hasidic philosophy|''Hasidus'']].<ref name=\"science.co.il\"/> \nDepending on the institution's stance, the weight and role assigned to Talmud particularly, and in fact to textual-skills generally, will differ re men's yeshivot, and between ''midrashot''.<ref name=\"Lilith\"/>\nSee [[Yeshiva #Curriculum]] for the general content of each topic. \n\n[[Religious Zionist]] and [[Modern Orthodox Judaism|Modern Orthodox]] ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' include the [[Religious Kibbutz Movement]]'s [[Ein_HaNetziv#Education|Ein HaNatziv]] and [[Migdal Oz (seminary)|Migdal Oz]], sister school of [[Yeshivat Har Etzion]].\nTreatment of Tanakh and Jewish philosophy, often referred to here as [[Jewish thought|''Machshava'']],  will typically be text-focused, built around [[chavruta]]-based study as at yeshivot.<ref name=\"Lilith\"/>\nThis entails paired-study where assigned sources are prepared for ''[[shiur]]'', a lecture delivered as a discursive-review.\nAt some institutions, [[Talmud]] is studied directly, also as at men's {{lang|he-Latn|[[yeshiva|yeshivot]]}}, if less intensively\n(see [[Women in Judaism #Joseph Solovetchik]]).\nRegardless, Jewish law will generally be studied with ''practice'' in view: i.e., as opposed to [[Yeshiva#Jewish_law|at a men's Yeshiva]], where the derivation is from Talmudic sources through codification \n(At [[Matan_Women's_Institute_for_Torah_Studies|Matan]], [[Nishmat (midrasha)|Nishmat]] and [[Midreshet Lindenbaum]] the treatment is Talmud-based;\nsee also [[Drisha Institute]].<ref>[https://www.drisha.co.il/ drisha.co.il]: \"\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05d4 \u05dc\u05e0\u05e9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d4\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d5\u05ea \u05dc\u05d4\u05e2\u05de\u05d9\u05e7 \u05d5\u05dc\u05d2\u05d3\u05d5\u05dc \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4\"</ref>)\n''Midrashot'' additionally focus on the writings of [[Rav Kook]], and ''[[Torat Eretz Yisrael]]'' in general.\n\nThe [[Haredi]] aligned seminaries - for example [[Beth Jacob Jerusalem]] - are modeled on the [[Beis Yaakov]] teacher-training seminary established by [[Sarah Schenirer]].\n(''Beis Yaakov'' almost invariably refers to high school, while \"Seminary\" is used for a post-high school institution.)\nSeminaries are typically more conservative in their approach than ''Midrashot'':\nselections from the Talmud may be studied, but only in the context of other classes, especially philosophy and Musar; \nthese institutions then also assign less weight to textual skills,<ref name=\"Lilith\"/> with content delivered primarily via lecture.\n(See [[Bais Yaakov #Curriculum]], [[Women in Judaism #Yisrael Meir Kagan]].)\n[[Bais_Yaakov#Hasidic_schools|Hasidic-aligned institutions]], for example [[Beth Rivkah]], are similarly positioned; their curricula differ in that they emphasize the works of their respective [[Rebbe]]. \nParallel to their academic content, most Seminaries also focus on [[Hashkafa#Gender_roles|the role of women in Torah]] - covering topics such as ''[[Tzniut]]'' (modesty), ''[[Shalom Bayit]]'' (\"domestic peace\") and ''[[Chinuch]]'' (education of one's children) - with these classes emphasizing ''values'', as opposed to sources. <ref name=\"Lilith\"/>\n(Several ''Midrashot'' similarly.<ref name =\"tal\"/>)\n\nMany diaspora-based Orthodox Jewish girls attend a ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}'', or \u201csem\u201d, in Israel for a year or more following high school; \nseveral ''midrashot'' and seminaries offer special programs, for example ''Shana Ba'aretz'' at Nishmat, or  the \"Overseas Program\" at [[Midreshet HaRova]].\nAdditional to Torah study, these usually include <ref name=\"Lilith\"/> [[Tourism_in_Israel|touring of Israel]], [[Shabbaton]]s in various communities, and often volunteer work in local schools and hospitals, and seminars with journalists and politicians.\nSome institutions accommodate  [[baal teshuva|the newly observant]] with similar year-programs, designed to build knowledge and skills; well known are [[Neve Yerushalayim]], [[Mayanot]], and [[Machon Roni]].\n\n===Certifications===\nIn the Religious Zionist community women often continue their studies at one of the midrasha-affiliated [[List_of_universities_and_colleges_in_Israel#Colleges|teacher training colleges]], which offer a Torah-program in conjunction with the [[B.Ed.]] degree; \n([[masters degree|masters' level]]) specializations are often offered in ''Tanakh''  or ''Machshavah''. \n[[Bar-Ilan University]] operates a ''midrasha'', and students in all disciplines may then continue Torah study in parallel with their academic studies (with a requirement of at least seven courses in Judaism<ref>[https://midrasha.biu.ac.il/en/node/406 Bar-Ilan ''Midrasha'']</ref>).\n[[Machon Tal]], <ref name =\"tal\">[https://www.jct.ac.il/%d7%a7%d7%9e%d7%a4%d7%95%d7%a1%d7%99%d7%9d/%d7%a7%d7%9e%d7%a4%d7%95%d7%a1-%d7%98%d7%9c/%d7%9e%d7%93%d7%a8%d7%a9%d7%aa-%d7%98%d7%9c/%d7%90%d7%95%d7%93%d7%95%d7%aa \u05de\u05d3\u05e8\u05e9\u05ea-\u05d8\u05dc], jct.ac.il</ref> associated with JCT, the [[Jerusalem College of Technology]], similarly offers degrees in engineering and management. \n\nMost Haredi and Hasidic seminaries likewise offer certificates, and sometimes degrees, in Education. \nThe two year certificates are through the [[:he:\u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df \u05d4\u05e0\u05e8\u05d9\u05d9\u05d8\u05d4 \u05e1\u05d0\u05dc\u05d3 |Szold Institute]], and are recognized by the [[Israel Ministry of Education]] as equivalent to the [[bagrut|national matriculation]].<ref>[https://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/headlines-breaking-stories/1395928/ministry-education-recognizes-teaching-certificates-matriculation-paves-way-charedi-women-pursue-college-israel.html discussion in the theyeshivaworld.com]</ref>\nBeth Rivkah offers a B.Ed. jointly with the [[:He:\u05e9\u05d0\u05e0\u05df_-_\u05d4\u05de\u05db\u05dc\u05dc\u05d4_\u05d4\u05d0\u05e7\u05d3\u05de\u05d9\u05ea_\u05d4\u05d3\u05ea\u05d9\u05ea_\u05dc\u05d7\u05d9\u05e0\u05d5\u05da|Shaanan Religious College of Education]].\n[[Jerusalem_College_of_Technology#Branches|JCT's Lustig Campus]] in [[Ramat Gan]] hosts degree programs for Haredi and Hasidic women;\nsee also [[The Haredi Campus - The Academic College Ono]].\n\nMost ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' for English-speaking students are accredited by American colleges; see [[Yeshiva #College credit]]. \nSome ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' offer second-year programs with religious-studies classes in the morning and general-studies classes in the afternoons, allowing students to pursue a religious education and a general-studies education leading to a college degree simultaneously.\nThe Modern Orthodox [[Stern College for Women]] - in Manhattan, New York - combines Torah and University studies, as at Bar-Ilan;\nthe Haredi [[Touro_College_and_University_System#Undergraduate_schools|Lander College for Women]] similarly.\n\n==Other Programs==\nAs above, the term ''Midrasha'' is sometimes used for [[Cultural Judaism|pluralistic]], as opposed to [[orthodox Judaism|orthodox]], institutions. These are usually structured around continuing / [[adult education]], and accept both men and women. Examples are \nthe Ein Prat Midrasha<ref>[http://www.bogrim.org/en_index.html Ein Prat Midrasha Bogrim.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071101012427/http://www.bogrim.org/en_index.html |date=2007-11-01 }}</ref> in Israel, \nand the [[Florence Melton#Melton Schools|Melton School]]'s ''Midrasha'' in [[Cape Town]]. <ref>[https://meltoncapetown.org/midrasha/ Midrasha Adult Education Institute], meltoncapetown.org</ref>\n\nWithin the Orthodox community, continuing-education programs of this type are also offered, \nfor example by  [[Matan_Women's_Institute_for_Torah_Studies|Matan]] <ref>[https://www.matan.org.il/en/learn-en/lessons/ Classes], matan.org.il</ref>\nand ''Emunah''; <ref>[http://www.emunah.org.il/%d7%90%d7%9e%d7%95%d7%a0%d7%94-%d7%91%d7%a7%d7%94%d7%99%d7%9c%d7%94/%d7%91%d7%aa%d7%99-%d7%9e%d7%93%d7%a8%d7%a9/ \u05d1\u05ea\u05d9-\u05de\u05d3\u05e8\u05e9], emunah.org.il; with international branches, for example [http://emunah.co.za/ emunah.co.za]</ref>\nthese are limited to women.\nMany synagogues host a [[Kollel#Community_kollelim|\"Community Kollel\"]], which has a similar function, and offers adult education to both men and women (usually separately).\n\nIn the [[United States]], the term ''Midrasha'' is also used for programs where high school students can continue their Jewish education post [[bar mitzvah|bar]] / [[bat mitzvah]]. <ref>[https://www.midrasha.org/ midrasha.org]</ref>\n\n[[Midreshet Ben-Gurion]] - also known as Midreshet Sde Boker - is an educational center and boarding school in southern Israel.\n[[:he: \u05d0\u05e9\u05db\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05ea - \u05e4\u05d5\u05e8\u05d5\u05dd \u05de\u05e8\u05db\u05d6\u05d9 \u05e1\u05d9\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d5\u05ea\u05d5\u05d3\u05e2\u05d4 \u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9\u05ea|''Eshkolot'']] operates \"''midrashot''\" aimed at knowledge of the [[land of Israel]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==See also==\n* [[Beis Yaakov]]\n* [[Female seminary]]\n* [[Haredi Judaism #Education]]\n* [[Hashkafa #Gender roles]]\n* [[Jewish education #Girls' education]]  \n* [[List of Midrashot]] & [[List of yeshivas, midrashas and Hebrew schools in Israel #Midrashas]]\n* [[Orthodox Judaism #Diversity]]\n* [[Religious Zionism #Educational institutions]]\n* [[Ulpana]]\n* [[Women in Judaism]] and esp. [[Women in Judaism #Views on the education of women|#Views on the education of women]]\n\n{{OrthodoxJudaism}}\n{{Jewish education}}\n<!-- Categories -->\n[[Category:Jewish educational institutions]]\n[[Category:Modern Orthodox Judaism]]\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish schools for women]]\n", "text_old": "A '''''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}''''' ([[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]: {{hebrew|\u05de\u05d3\u05e8\u05e9\u05d4}}, pl. ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot/midrashas}}'') is an institute of [[Torah study]] for women, generally in [[Israel]], and roughly the equivalent of a [[yeshiva]] for men. \nAn alternative term, and translation, is '[[seminary]]' ({{hebrew|\u05e1\u05de\u05d9\u05e0\u05e8}}); <ref name=\"science.co.il\">[https://www.science.co.il/jewish-studies/Midrashot.php ''Midrashot''], science.co.il</ref> these are modeled on the [[Sarah_Schenirer#Teacher's_Seminary|institution established by Sarah Schenirer]] in 1923.\n\"''Midrasha''\" is often associated with Religious Zionist institutions, while \"Seminary\" refers to ''[[Haredi]]'' institutions.\nA ''midrasha'' that offers [[academic degree|degree studies]] is sometimes called a ''machon'' ({{hebrew|\u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df}}, institute).\n\nThe word \"''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}''\" is based on the term ''[[beit midrash]]'', \"house of study\".  It is [[cognate]] with the [[Arabic]] \"''{{transl|ar|[[madrasa|madrasah]]}}'',\" which also refers to a place of learning.\n\nThe term ''Midrasha'' is sometimes used  more widely, referring to [[Cultural Judaism|pluralistic]], as opposed to [[orthodox Judaism|orthodox]], educational  institutions.\nIt may also refer to [[field school]]s that organize seminars and nature field trips.<ref name=\"science.co.il\"/>\n\n==Structure==\n===Curriculum===\n''{{lang|he-Latn|Midrashot}}'' and seminaries vary in curriculum and [[Orthodox Judaism#Social and philosophic differences|philosophy]]. \n<ref name=\"Lilith\">[https://www.lilith.org/blog/2014/09/a-modest-year-in-israel-when-young-women-go-to-seminary/ A Modest Year in Israel: When Young Women go to \u201cSeminary\u201d]. [[Lilith (magazine)|''Lilith'']], 2014 </ref>\nAll cover [[Tanakh]] (Hebrew Bible), [[Jewish philosophy]], [[Halacha|Jewish law]]  and [[Musar Literature|Musar (Ethics)]] / [[Hasidic philosophy|''Hasidus'']].<ref name=\"science.co.il\"/> \nDepending on the institution's stance, the weight and role assigned to Talmud particularly, and in fact to textual-skills generally, will differ re men's yeshivot, and between ''midrashot''.<ref name=\"Lilith\"/>\nSee [[Yeshiva #Curriculum]] for the general content of each topic. \n\n[[Religious Zionist]] and [[Modern Orthodox Judaism|Modern Orthodox]] ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' include the [[Religious Kibbutz Movement]]'s [[Ein_HaNetziv#Education|Ein HaNatziv]] and [[Migdal Oz (seminary)|Migdal Oz]], sister school of [[Yeshivat Har Etzion]].\nTreatment of Tanakh and Jewish philosophy, often referred to here as [[Jewish thought|''Machshava'']],  will typically be text-focused, built around [[chavruta]]-based study as at yeshivot.<ref name=\"Lilith\"/>\nThis entails paired-study where assigned sources are prepared for ''[[shiur]]'', a lecture delivered as a discursive-review.\nAt some institutions, [[Talmud]] is studied directly, also as at men's {{lang|he-Latn|[[yeshiva|yeshivot]]}}, if less intensively\n(see [[Women in Judaism #Joseph Solovetchik]]).\nRegardless, Jewish law will generally be studied with ''practice'' in view: i.e., as opposed to [[Yeshiva#Jewish_law|at a men's Yeshiva]], where the derivation is from Talmudic sources through codification \n(At [[Matan_Women's_Institute_for_Torah_Studies|Matan]], [[Nishmat (midrasha)|Nishmat]] and [[Midreshet Lindenbaum]] the treatment is Talmud-based;\nsee also [[Drisha Institute]].<ref>[https://www.drisha.co.il/ drisha.co.il]: \"\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05d4 \u05dc\u05e0\u05e9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d4\u05de\u05d1\u05e7\u05e9\u05d5\u05ea \u05dc\u05d4\u05e2\u05de\u05d9\u05e7 \u05d5\u05dc\u05d2\u05d3\u05d5\u05dc \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4\"</ref>)\n''Midrashot'' additionally focus on the writings of [[Rav Kook]], and ''[[Torat Eretz Yisrael]]'' in general.\n\nThe [[Haredi]] aligned seminaries - for example [[Beth Jacob Jerusalem]] - are modeled on the [[Beis Yaakov]] teacher-training seminary established by [[Sarah Schenirer]].\n(''Beis Yaakov'' almost invariably refers to high school, while \"Seminary\" is used for a post-high school institution.)\nSeminaries are typically more conservative in their approach than ''Midrashot'':\nselections from the Talmud may be studied, but only in the context of other classes, especially philosophy and Musar; \nthese institutions then also assign less weight to textual skills,<ref name=\"Lilith\"/> with content delivered primarily via lecture.\n(See [[Bais Yaakov #Curriculum]], [[Women in Judaism #Yisrael Meir Kagan]].)\n[[Bais_Yaakov#Hasidic_schools|Hasidic-aligned institutions]], for example [[Beth Rivkah]], are similarly positioned; their curricula differ in that they emphasize the works of their respective [[Rebbe]]. \nParallel to their academic content, most Seminaries also focus on [[Hashkafa#Gender_roles|the role of women in Torah]] - covering topics such as ''[[Tzniut]]'' (modesty), ''[[Shalom Bayit]]'' (\"domestic peace\") and ''[[Chinuch]]'' (education of one's children) - with these classes emphasizing ''values'', as opposed to sources. <ref name=\"Lilith\"/>\n(Several ''Midrashot'' similarly.<ref name =\"tal\"/>)\n\nMany diaspora-based Orthodox Jewish girls attend a ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}'', or \u201csem\u201d, in Israel for a year or more following high school; \nseveral ''midrashot'' and seminaries offer special programs, for example ''Shana Ba'aretz'' at Nishmat, or  the \"Overseas Program\" at [[Midreshet HaRova]].\nAdditional to Torah study, these usually include <ref name=\"Lilith\"/> [[Tourism_in_Israel|touring of Israel]], [[Shabbaton]]s in various communities, and often volunteer work in local schools and hospitals, and seminars with journalists and politicians.\nSome institutions accommodate  [[baal teshuva|the newly observant]] with similar year-programs, designed to build knowledge and skills; well known are [[Neve Yerushalayim]], [[Mayanot]], and [[Machon Roni]].\n\n===Certifications===\nIn the Religious Zionist community women often continue their studies at one of the midrasha-affiliated [[List_of_universities_and_colleges_in_Israel#Colleges|teacher training colleges]], which offer a Torah-program in conjunction with the [[B.Ed.]] degree; \n([[masters degree|masters' level]]) specializations are often offered in ''Tanakh''  or ''Machshavah''. \n[[Bar-Ilan University]] operates a ''midrasha'', and students in all disciplines may then continue Torah study in parallel with their academic studies (with a requirement of at least seven courses in Judaism<ref>[https://midrasha.biu.ac.il/en/node/406 Bar-Ilan ''Midrasha'']</ref>).\n[[Machon Tal]], <ref name =\"tal\">[https://www.jct.ac.il/%d7%a7%d7%9e%d7%a4%d7%95%d7%a1%d7%99%d7%9d/%d7%a7%d7%9e%d7%a4%d7%95%d7%a1-%d7%98%d7%9c/%d7%9e%d7%93%d7%a8%d7%a9%d7%aa-%d7%98%d7%9c/%d7%90%d7%95%d7%93%d7%95%d7%aa \u05de\u05d3\u05e8\u05e9\u05ea-\u05d8\u05dc], jct.ac.il</ref> associated with JCT, the [[Jerusalem College of Technology]], similarly offers degrees in engineering and management. \n\nMost Haredi and Hasidic seminaries likewise offer certificates, and sometimes degrees, in Education. The two year certificates are through the [[:he:\u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df \u05d4\u05e0\u05e8\u05d9\u05d9\u05d8\u05d4 \u05e1\u05d0\u05dc\u05d3 |Szold Institute]], and are recognized by the [[Israel Ministry of Education]] as equivalent to the [[bagrut|national matriculation]].<ref>[https://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/headlines-breaking-stories/1395928/ministry-education-recognizes-teaching-certificates-matriculation-paves-way-charedi-women-pursue-college-israel.html discussion in the theyeshivaworld.com]</ref>\n[[Jerusalem_College_of_Technology#Branches|JCT's Lustig Campus]] in [[Ramat Gan]] hosts degree programs for Haredi and Hasidic women;\nsee also [[The Haredi Campus - The Academic College Ono]].\n\nMost ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' for English-speaking students are accredited by American colleges; see [[Yeshiva #College credit]]. \nSome ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' offer second-year programs with religious-studies classes in the morning and general-studies classes in the afternoons, allowing students to pursue a religious education and a general-studies education leading to a college degree simultaneously.\nThe Modern Orthodox [[Stern College for Women]] - in Manhattan, New York - combines Torah and University studies, as at Bar-Ilan;\nthe Haredi [[Touro_College_and_University_System#Undergraduate_schools|Lander College for Women]] similarly.\n\n==Other Programs==\nAs above, the term ''Midrasha'' is sometimes used for [[Cultural Judaism|pluralistic]], as opposed to [[orthodox Judaism|orthodox]], institutions. These are usually structured around continuing / [[adult education]], and accept both men and women. Examples are \nthe Ein Prat Midrasha<ref>[http://www.bogrim.org/en_index.html Ein Prat Midrasha Bogrim.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071101012427/http://www.bogrim.org/en_index.html |date=2007-11-01 }}</ref> in Israel, \nand the [[Florence Melton#Melton Schools|Melton School]]'s ''Midrasha'' in [[Cape Town]]. <ref>[https://meltoncapetown.org/midrasha/ Midrasha Adult Education Institute], meltoncapetown.org</ref>\n\nWithin the Orthodox community, continuing-education programs of this type are also offered, \nfor example by  [[Matan_Women's_Institute_for_Torah_Studies|Matan]] <ref>[https://www.matan.org.il/en/learn-en/lessons/ Classes], matan.org.il</ref>\nand ''Emunah''; <ref>[http://www.emunah.org.il/%d7%90%d7%9e%d7%95%d7%a0%d7%94-%d7%91%d7%a7%d7%94%d7%99%d7%9c%d7%94/%d7%91%d7%aa%d7%99-%d7%9e%d7%93%d7%a8%d7%a9/ \u05d1\u05ea\u05d9-\u05de\u05d3\u05e8\u05e9], emunah.org.il; with international branches, for example [http://emunah.co.za/ emunah.co.za]</ref>\nthese are limited to women.\nMany synagogues host a [[Kollel#Community_kollelim|\"Community Kollel\"]], which has a similar function, and offers adult education to both men and women (usually separately).\n\nIn the [[United States]], the term ''Midrasha'' is also used for programs where high school students can continue their Jewish education post [[bar mitzvah|bar]] / [[bat mitzvah]]. <ref>[https://www.midrasha.org/ midrasha.org]</ref>\n\n[[Midreshet Ben-Gurion]] - also known as Midreshet Sde Boker - is an educational center and boarding school in southern Israel.\n[[:he: \u05d0\u05e9\u05db\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05ea - \u05e4\u05d5\u05e8\u05d5\u05dd \u05de\u05e8\u05db\u05d6\u05d9 \u05e1\u05d9\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d5\u05ea\u05d5\u05d3\u05e2\u05d4 \u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9\u05ea|''Eshkolot'']] operates \"''midrashot''\" aimed at knowledge of the [[land of Israel]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==See also==\n* [[Beis Yaakov]]\n* [[Female seminary]]\n* [[Haredi Judaism #Education]]\n* [[Hashkafa #Gender roles]]\n* [[Jewish education #Girls' education]]  \n* [[List of Midrashot]] & [[List of yeshivas, midrashas and Hebrew schools in Israel #Midrashas]]\n* [[Orthodox Judaism #Diversity]]\n* [[Religious Zionism #Educational institutions]]\n* [[Ulpana]]\n* [[Women in Judaism]] and esp. [[Women in Judaism #Views on the education of women|#Views on the education of women]]\n\n{{OrthodoxJudaism}}\n{{Jewish education}}\n<!-- Categories -->\n[[Category:Jewish educational institutions]]\n[[Category:Modern Orthodox Judaism]]\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish schools for women]]\n", "name_user": "Fintor", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCertifications", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midrasha"}
{"title_page": "Yangon University of Foreign Languages", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Yangon University of Foreign Languages\n| native_name = {{my|\u101b\u1014\u103a\u1000\u102f\u1014\u103a\u1014\u102d\u102f\u1004\u103a\u1004\u1036\u1001\u103c\u102c\u1038\u1018\u102c\u101e\u102c\u1010\u1000\u1039\u1000\u101e\u102d\u102f\u101c\u103a<!--UNICODE, DO NOT INSERT ZAWGYI-->}}<br>{{IPA-my|j\u00e0\u0270\u0303\u0261\u00f2\u028a\u0270\u0303 n\u00e0\u026a\u0270\u0303\u014b\u00e0\u0270\u0303d\u0291\u00e1 b\u00e0\u00f0\u00e0 t\u025b\u0294k\u0259\u03b8\u00f2|IPA}}\n| native_name_lang = bur\n| other_name = University of Foreign Languages, Yangon\n| former_name = Foreign Languages Institution, Institute of Foreign Languages\n| image = File:YUFL Logo.png\n| latin_name = Universitas Yangon Linguas Peregrinas\n| motto = \u1021\u1005\u1025\u103a\u1021\u101c\u102c\u101d\u1004\u1037\u103a\u1011\u100a\u103a YUFL\n| motto_lang = bur\n| mottoeng = YUFL with its prestigious practices.\n| established = {{start date and age|16 January 1964}}\n| type = Public\n| affiliation = Ministry of Education, Department of Higher education\n| academic_affiliation = Mandalay University of Foreign Languages\n| rector = Dr. Kyi Shwin\n| address = 119/131, University Avenue Rd.,Ward (10), Kamayut Township, West District\n| city = Yangon\n| province = Yangon Region\n| country = Myanmar (Burma)\n| coordinates = {{coord|16|49|29.3|N|96|8|29.7|E|display=inline,title}}\n| campus = Urban\n| language = English , Burmese\n| colours = Blue, red, yellow, white  {{color box|#0000FE}}{{color box|#CB0030}}{{color box|#FEFD02}}{{color box|#FEFEFE}}\n| website = {{url|https://www.yufl.edu.mm/demo}}\n| logo = File:YUFLLogo.webp\n| faculty = 303\n}}[[File:YUFL Campus Drone.jpg|thumb|435x435px|A bird's eye view of YUFL Campus|alt=|left]]The '''Yangon University of Foreign Languages''' (also the '''University of Foreign Languages, Yangon''') ({{lang-my|\u1014\u102d\u102f\u1004\u103a\u1004\u1036\u1001\u103c\u102c\u1038\u1018\u102c\u101e\u102c\u1010\u1000\u1039\u1000\u101e\u102d\u102f\u101c\u103a (\u101b\u1014\u103a\u1000\u102f\u1014\u103a)}} {{IPA-my|n\u00e0\u026a\u0270\u0303\u014b\u00e0\u0270\u0303d\u0291\u00e1 b\u00e0\u00f0\u00e0 t\u025b\u0294k\u0259\u03b8\u00f2 j\u00e0\u0270\u0303\u0261\u00f2\u028a\u0270\u0303|j\u00e0\u0270\u0303\u0261\u00f2\u028a\u0270\u0303 n\u00e0\u026a\u0270\u0303\u014b\u00e0\u0270\u0303d\u0291\u00e1 b\u00e0\u00f0\u00e0 t\u025b\u0294k\u0259\u03b8\u00f2}}), located in [[Yangon]], is the leading university for the study of foreign languages in [[Myanmar]]. The university offers full-time four-year bachelor's degree programs, and part-time diploma programs in the study of several Asian and European languages. The university is popular with students interested in careers in the tourism industry or finding work overseas.<ref name=mt-1>{{cite news | title=Learning to speak another tongue | url=http://www.myanmar.com/myanmartimes/MyanmarTimes13-255/e010.htm | date=2005-02-21 | author=Thiha Zaw | newspaper=The Myanmar Times}}</ref><ref name=\"mt-2\">{{cite news|author=Kyaw Soe Linn and Phyo Wai Kyaw|date=2007-05-14|title=Language training centers open doors to new worlds|url=http://www.mmtimes.com/feature/edu/edu002.htm|url-status=dead|newspaper=The Myanmar Times|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720094651/http://www.mmtimes.com/feature/edu/edu002.htm|archivedate=2008-07-20}}</ref> The university is one of the leading universities of Myanmar and admits approximately 800 students annually based on their [[University Entrance Examination]] scores.\n\n\n\nThe rector is Dr. Kyi Shwin and pro-rectors are Dr. Mi Mi Aung and Dr. Yin Myo Wai.\n\nYangon University of Foreign Languages is one of the two language universities in Myanmar alongside with [[Mandalay University of Foreign Languages]].\n\n\n\n\n\n<br />\n== History ==\n\nThe '''Foreign Languages Institution''' later to become the '''University of Foreign Languages''' began its existence on the top floor of Chartered Bank Building on Pansodan Street on 16 January 1964. U Ba Myint served as a Principal from 8 January 1964 to 7 February 1965. The Institute started with 4 language departments: [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]] and [[Russian language|Russian]]. The initial enrollment was 53 students in full-time [[diploma]], part-time [[diploma]], state scholars and language proficiency classes. In 1965, the Chinese Department was established and U Yu Khin became Principal on 8 February 1965.[[File:Charter-Bank-1964.jpg|400px|thumb|Chartered Bank Building|alt=|left]]\n\nThe Institute was relocated to [https://goo.gl/maps/AW2Gzti9XnLA5tkN7 119-131 University Avenue, Yangon], its current location and U Yu Khin was still working as the principal at that time and he continued working until 30 April 1971. In that academic year, the admission increased to 205 students. Italian language programme was offered from 1970 to 1980. U Win Maung became Principal on 1 May 1971.<mapframe latitude=\"16.824814\" longitude=\"96.141556\" zoom=\"13\" width=\"400\" height=\"300\" align=\"left\">{\n  \"type\": \"FeatureCollection\",\n  \"features\": [\n    {\n      \"type\": \"Feature\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"marker-color\": \"0e39f2\"\n      },\n      \"geometry\": {\n        \"type\": \"Point\",\n        \"coordinates\": [\n          96.14148616790773,\n          16.824588380443036\n        ]\n      }\n    }\n  ]\n}</mapframe>\n\n\nThe Institute was transferred direct control of [[Ministry of Education (Myanmar)|Ministry of Education]] to [[Department of Higher Education (Myanmar)|Department of Higher Education]] on 15 March 1972. The '''Foreign Languages Institution''' was renamed '''Institute of Foreign Languages''' and the-then principal U Win Maung administered the Institute till 17 September 1972. Enrollment increased to 383.\n\nU Tin Aung Soe (from 28 September 1972 to 10 August 1979), U Win Maung (from 10 August 1979 to 7 August 1980), U Sai Aung Tun (from 7 May 1980 to 3 November 1985), U Myo Nyunt (from 16 December 1985 to 3 February 1991) and Dr. Soe Win (from 4 February 1991 to 15 January 1997) served as principals of '''Institute of Foreign Languages''' respectively.\n\n\nBefore the establishment of the language departments, [[English language|English]] courses were first offered in 1969 and [[Burmese language|Myanmar]] language courses were started in 1974 with the faculty members from [[Yangon University]]. More and more language departments were added over the years: English Department was established in 1984; Myanmar Department, in 1985; Thai Department, in 1989; and Korean Department, in 1993. Admission increased every year and reached 1179 in 1995\u201396 academic year. At that time, classrooms were located in the Main Building (a two-storeyed building), the Myawady Buildings (4 two-storeyed buildings), and the OB Buildings (7 one-storeyed buildings).\n\nThe Institute was upgraded to the [[university]] level and became the '''Yangon University of Foreign Languages''' on 2 October 1996 and in addition to the currently offered courses, [[Bachelor's degree|Bachelor's Degree]] and [[Master's degree]] Programmes were launched, with the enrollment of 1314 students.\n\n\nSince its upgrade to a university, the-then principal Dr. Soe Win served as the [[Prorector|pro-rector]] (from 15 January 1997 to 11 June 1997) and as the [[Rector (academia)|rector]] (From 12 June 1997 to 3 June 2005). After him, Dr. Aung Aung Min served as the [[Prorector|pro-rector]] (from 1 July 2005 to 20 October 2005), Dr. Myo Myint as the [[Rector (academia)|rector]] (from 21 October 2005 to 30 March 2011), Dr. Tin Maung Tun as the [[Prorector|pro-rector]] (from 30 March 2011 to 18 April 2011), Dr. Lwin Lwin Soe as the [[Rector (academia)|rector]] (from 29 April 2011 to 14 March 2016) and Dr Yee Yee Maw as the [[Prorector|pro-rector]] (from 15 March 2016 to 12 October 2016). Dr. Kyi Shwin has been serving as the [[Rector (academia)|rector]] of the '''Yangon University of Foreign Languages''' since 13 October 2016.\n\nThe Italian Language Department was reestablished in 2014\u20132015 academic year. Students\u2019 admission increases every year and in 2016\u20132017 academic year, it reached to (383000), taking [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]], [[Master of Arts|M.A]], M.A (Q), [[Diploma]], [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A]] courses as well as CHRD(Center of Human Resource Development) evening courses.\n\nDepartment of [[Linguistics]], Department of [[Oriental studies|Oriental Studies]], Department of [[Philosophy]], Department of [[History]] and Department of [[International studies|International Studies]] were established in 1988.  \n\n<br />\n== Campus ==\n<mapframe text=\"YUFL Campus Map\" width=\"453\" height=\"363\" zoom=\"18\" latitude=\"16.824588\" longitude=\"96.141572\" align=\"right\">\n{\n  \"type\": \"FeatureCollection\",\n  \"features\": [\n    {\n      \"type\": \"Feature\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"marker-symbol\": \"-number\",\n        \"marker-color\": \"0e39f2\"\n      },\n      \"geometry\": {\n        \"type\": \"Point\",\n        \"coordinates\": [\n          96.141613,\n          16.824732\n        ]\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"type\": \"Feature\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"marker-symbol\": \"-number\",\n        \"marker-color\": \"0e39f2\"\n      },\n      \"geometry\": {\n        \"type\": \"Point\",\n        \"coordinates\": [\n          96.141307,\n          16.823893\n        ]\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"type\": \"Feature\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"marker-symbol\": \"-number\",\n        \"marker-color\": \"0e39f2\"\n      },\n      \"geometry\": {\n        \"type\": \"Point\",\n        \"coordinates\": [\n          96.142222,\n          16.824599\n        ]\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"type\": \"Feature\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"marker-symbol\": \"-number\",\n        \"marker-color\": \