n      },\n      \"geometry\": {\n        \"type\": \"Point\",\n        \"coordinates\": [\n          96.137216,\n          16.818075\n        ]\n      }\n    }\n  ]\n}\n</mapframe>\n\n=== Buildings ===\n \nThe university is located in [https://goo.gl/maps/AW2Gzti9XnLA5tkN7 119-131 University Avenue, Yangon] and it has a total of 11 buildings with eight of them being used for education purpose and the rest three being used for general purpose. The 8 academic buildings are \n\n# Main Buiding (MB)\n# New Building (NB)\n# Library and Resource Center (LRC)\n# Extension Building (EB)\n# Center of Excellence Building (COE)\n# Recreation Center (RC)\n# Modernized Canteen and Oriental Building (OB), and\n# International Students Hall (ISH) \n\n\nThe Main Building was handed over from the [[Ministry of Culture (Myanmar)|Ministry of Culture]] in 1966. 4-storeyed New Building, the Library and Resource Centre\u00a0 (LRC), Extension Building (EB), Centre of Excellence (COE) and Recreation Centre (RC), Centre of Excellence Building and Modernized Canteen and The International Students Hall (ISH) were constructed in the fiscal years 1995\u201396, 1997\u201398, \u00a02008\u201309, 2013\u201314, 2014\u201315,2015\u201316 and 2019-20 respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yufl.edu.mm/demo/introduction-and-history/|title=Introduction and History {{!}} YUFL|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Housing ===\nThe accommodation is not mixed and the availability is limited. There are 2 hostels available for YUFL students. They are-\n\n# Adipadi Hostel (for men),and\n# Akari Hostel (for women)\n\nBoth hostels are located near YUFL Campus and is built side to side at the corner of Inya Road and Thahtone Road in Thahtone Compound which is owned by [[Department of Higher Education (Myanmar)|Department of Higher Education]], [[Ministry of Education (Myanmar)|Ministry of Education]].\n\nIt is near to Hledan which is a major hub in Yangon and is close to many shopping complex; Junction Square Complex, Times City Complex, Hledan Center and Gamonepwint Saneiknyein Shopping center.\n\nIt is also close to other educational institutes such as [[University of Medicine 1, Yangon|University of Medicine 1, Yangon Thahtone Campus,]] [[University of Medicine 1, Yangon|University of Medicine 1,Yangon Pyay Campus]], [[Yangon University of Education]], [[University of Yangon|Yangon University]], [[Basic Education High School No. 2 Kamayut|B.E.H.S 2 Kamayut]] and [[Practising School Yangon Institute of Education]]. \n\n== Programs ==\n\n=== Regular Programs ===\nThere are [[Undergraduate education|undergraduate]] programme, [[Master's degree|master]] programme, [[doctorate]] progrmme that are running as part-time as well as full-time classes in YUFL. Besides, there are [[postgraduate diploma]] and [[Academic certificate|certificate]]s under the Center of Human Resource Development.\n\n===== Undergraduate Programs =====\nUnder the [[Undergraduate education|undergraduate]] progrmmes, there are eight languages offering bachelor's degree in [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Korean language|Korean]], [[Russian language|Russian]] and [[Thai language|Thai]]. It takes four years to complete the degree.\n\n===== Master Programs =====\nThe Master programmes including Qualifying classes are now being offered in the Departments of [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]],[[Korean language|Korean]], [[Russian language|Russian]] and [[Thai language|Thai]] as two year full-time programs. Unlike other Master programs, Master's degree for English is one year full-time programme. \n\n===== Doctrate Programs =====\n[[Doctorate|Doctrate]] Programmes are now being offered to  candidates who passed [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] entrance exam to attend [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] preliminary Classes. Another channel to join the [[Doctorate|Doctrate]] programme targeted to senior [[Faculty (division)|faculty]] members. [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] Programmes are now opened in the Departments of [[Chinese language|Chinese]] and [[Korean language|Korean]] Languages.\n\n==== Foreign student Programs ====\nThere are numbers of students who came from different parts of the world to seek the opportunity to learn [[Burmese language|Myanmar]] as foreign language. [[Burmese language|Myanmar]] Language programmes are conducted in YUFL for the four year-[[Bachelor's degree|bachelor degree]], two-year full-time [[diploma]] and one year Myanmar language proficiency Programmes (Basic, Intermediate & Advanced Levels) \n\n==== Human Resource Development courses ====\n\n==== Diploma Programmes ====\nThere are full-time and part-time postgraduate diploma programmes in YUFL. \n\n===== Full-time Postgraduate Diploma Programmes =====\nThere are full-time postgraduate [[diploma]] degree programme in [[English language|English]] and [[Italian language|Italian]] Languages. For English Language Diploma, students have to attend one year and for students who attend the Italian Language in Diploma Degree have to spend two years.\n\n===== Part-Time  Postgraduate Diploma Programmes =====\nUnder the part-time postgraduate [[diploma]] degree program,[[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Korean language|Korean]], [[Russian language|Russian]] and [[Thai language|Thai]] programmes are offered. All languages in part-time programmes require four years to complete the degree. [[Diploma]] in [[Linguistics]] is now offered in YUFL as a part-time postgraduate diploma programme. Students have to spend 2 years for Diploma in Linguistics programme.\n\nA significant step toward the YUFL as a center of foreign studies, two part-time postgraduate diploma programmes; Diploma in [[Sinology|China Studies]] and Diploma in [[International relations|International Relations]] are just being opened in June 2019 as an initial studies programme. For Diploma in [[Sinology|China Studies]] Degree, students have to attend two year and for students who attend the Diploma in [[International relations|International Relations]] Degree have to spend nine months.\n\n==== Certificate Programmes ====\nAs a language-oriented university, YUFL is well known in its [[Academic certificate|certificate]] programmes. \n\nThere are some programmes targeting to students who have just passed but waiting to join the university. High School graduate students can also join such certificate programmes as [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Korean language|Korean]], [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and [[Thai language|Thai]] languages.\n\n* Provide evening language proficiency classes from 5 to 7 p.m. in foreign languages as well as Myanmar as a foreign language.\n* Accept both [[graduates]] & non-graduates \u00a0 \u2013 scheduled at Basic, Intermediate & Advanced levels.\n* Provides 12 to 24 week courses at each level \u2013 tailored to cater to the needs of those working & young students who are eager to learn foreign languages.\n\nAccording to the local demand, YUFL also introduces the two new certificate programmes; Certificate in English [[Interpretation (logic)|Interpretation]] Course and Certificate in French Translation and Interpretation. Both programs needs to spend 6 months to get certificate. \n\n=== Myanmar as foreign language for foreigners in YUFL ===\n[[Burmese language|Myanmar]] Language as foreign language programmes are also offered to foreign students. Like other programmes focused on local students, [[Burmese language|Myanmar]] language for foreign students being offered in degree programmes in [[Bachelor's degree|Bachelor]], [[Diploma]] and [[Academic certificate|Certificate]]. For bachelor's degree, student has to spend four years while Diploma degree needs two years and Myanmar Language Proficiency in Basic, Intermediate and Advance Levels needs one year to complete the courses.\n\nThe like HRD programme in other languages, there are certificate courses on Myanmar Language for foreigners who have to spend six months for Basic I and another three months for Basic II.\n\n=== Short training courses ===\nLanguage courses for officials from various ministries that accept for scholars going abroad for further studies and government personnel who need foreign languages in their work.\n\n* English language proficiency course for [[Myanmar Army|Armed Forces Officers]].\n* English language proficiency course for officers form [[Ministry of Defence (Myanmar)|Ministry of Defence]] and [[Ministry of Home Affairs (Myanmar)|Ministry of Home Affairs]]\n* Language proficiency course for state scholars in Chinese, English, French, German, Japan, Korean, Russian, Thai\n* English language proficiency course for state scholars (JDS)\n*[[Test of English as a Foreign Language|TOEFL]] preparation course for state scholars from different ministries\n\n== Governance ==\nFrom 1964 to 1996, the '''Foreign Languages Institution''' which later became the '''Institute of Foreign Languages''' was headed by [[principal (academia)|principal]]s.\n\n# U Ba Myint: 8 January 1964 - 7 February 1965:\n# U Yu Khin: 8 February 1965 - 30 April 1971\n# U TIn Aung Soe: 28 September 1972 - 10 August 1979\n# U WIn Maung: 10 August 1979 - 7 August 1980\n# U Sai Aung Tun7 May 1980 - 3 November 1985 \n# U Myo Nyunt16 December 1985 - 3 February 1991\n# Dr. Soe Win: 4 February 1991 - 15 January 1997\n\nThe institute was upgraded to the university level and became the Yangon University of Foreign Languages on 2 October 1996. Since 1996, the university has been headed by academic dean known as  [[Rector (academia)|rector]] and [[Prorector|pro-rector]].\n\n# Dr. Soe Win (Pro-rector): 15 January 1997 - 11 June 1997\n# Dr. Soe Win (Rector): 12 June 1997 to 3 June 2005 \n# Dr. Aung Aung Min (Pro-Rector): 1 July 2005 - 20 October 2005\n# Dr. Myo Myint (Rector): 21 October 2005 - 30 March 2011\n# Dr. Myo Han (Pro-Rector): 19 May 2005 to 30 May 2015\n# Dr. Tin Mg Tun (Pro-Rector): 30 March 2011 - 18 April 2011\n# Dr. Lwin Lwin Soe (Rector): 29 April 2011 - 14 March 2016\n# Dr. Tin Htwe (Pro-Rector): 8 July 2011 to 17 March 2016\n# Dr. Yee Maw (Pro-Rector): 15 March 2016 - 12 October 2016 \n# Dr. Mi Mi Aung (Pro-rector): 31 March 2016 \u2013 Present: \n# Dr. Kyi Shwin (Rector): 13 October 2016 \u2013 Present\n#Dr. YIn Myo Thu: (Pro-rector)19 June 2018 \u2013 Present\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Sai Sai Kham Hlaing]]\n*[[Rebecca Win]]\n*[[Phway Phway]]\n*[[Myint Aye]]\n*[[Wyne Lay]]\n*[[Ah Moon]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Mandalay University of Foreign Languages]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Yangon]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Yangon Region]]\n[[Category:Arts and Science universities in Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1964]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in Burma]]\n[[Category:Academic language institutions]]\n__INDEX__\n", "name_user": "Duwonsoetun", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yangon_University_of_Foreign_Languages"}
{"title_page": "Flag of Croatia", "text_new": "{{short description|State symbol of Croatia}}\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox flag\n| Name         = Croatia\n| Image        = Flag of Croatia.svg\n| Alt        = [[Flag of Croatia]]\n| Nickname     = Trobojnica<br>(The Tricolour)\n| Morenicks    =\n| Use          = 111000\n| Symbol       =\n| Proportion   = 1:2\n| Adoption     = 21 December 1990\n| Design       = A horizontal tricolour of red, white, and blue with the Coat of Arms of Croatia in the centre.\n| Designer     = [[Miroslav \u0160utej]]<ref name=Sabor>{{cite web |url=http://www.sabor.hr/lgs.axd?t=16&id=19045 |title=Flag of the Republic of Croatia |publisher=[[Croatian Parliament]] |accessdate=30 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614173058/http://www.sabor.hr/lgs.axd?t=16&id=19045 |archive-date=14 June 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| Type         = National\n| Image2       = Civil Ensign of Croatia.svg\n| Nickname2    =\n| Morenicks2   =\n| Use2         = 000110\n| Symbol2      =\n| Proportion2  = 2:3\n| Adoption2    = 1992\n| Design2      = Three equal horizontal bands of red (top), white and blue superimposed by the Croatian coat of arms.\n| Designer2    =\n| Image3       = Naval Ensign of Croatia.svg\n| Nickname3    =\n| Morenicks3   =\n| Use3         = 000001\n| Symbol3      =\n| Proportion3  = 2:3\n| Adoption3    = 1992\n| Design3      = Three equal horizontal bands of red (top), white and blue superimposed by the emblem of the Croatian Navy.\n| Designer3    =\n}}\n<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=\ud83c\uddf8\ud83c\uddfb\ud83c\uddf8\ud83c\uddfb|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>The [[national flag|national]] '''flag of Croatia''' ({{lang-hr|Zastava Hrvatske}}) or '''The Tricolour''' ({{lang|hr|Trobojnica}}) is one of the state symbols of [[Croatia]]. It consists of three equal size, horizontal stripes in colours [[red]], [[white]] and [[blue]]. In the middle is the [[coat of arms of Croatia]].\n\n==History==\nThe flag combines the colours of the flags of the Kingdom of Croatia (red and white), the Kingdom of Slavonia (blue and white) and partially of the Kingdom of Dalmatia (blue and yellow). Those three kingdoms are the historic constituent states of the Croatian Kingdom.\n\nThe red-white-blue tricolour has been used as the Croatian flag since 1848, and the [[pan-Slavic colours]] are widely associated with [[romantic nationalism]]. While the [[Banovina of Croatia]] existed within the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]], it had a similar flag without the modern crown above the [[chequy]]. During the [[Independent State of Croatia]], the flag was like the modern, but without crown and there was the letter \"U\" at the top left of the flag. Also, the first field of Croatian chequy was white. While Croatia was part of the [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]] its [[Triband (flag)|tricolour]] was the same, but it had a five-pointed red star with a yellow border in place of the coat of arms. The star was replaced by the coat in May 1990, shortly after the first multiparty elections. The current flag and the coat of arms were officially adopted on 21 December 1990, about ten months before the proclamation of independence from Yugoslavia and a day before the Constitution of Croatia on 22 December 1990.\n\n==Shield==\nThe shield is in the red and white checks of Croatia. Above is a crown made of shields of its various regions. From left to right they are the ancient arms of Croatia, [[Republic of Ragusa|Dubrovnik]], [[Coat of arms of Dalmatia|Dalmatia]], [[Istria]] and [[Slavonia]].\n\n== Colours ==\n[[File:Croatian flag at the Knin Fortress 2015.jpg|thumb|right|[[Flag of Croatia on Knin Fortress]]]]\n[[File:Zastava na Sr\u0111u.JPG|thumb|right|The largest flying flag in Croatia, atop the [[Sr\u0111]] mountain over the city of [[Dubrovnik]]]]\nThe following colours are specified for use in the flag:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sabor.hr/Default.aspx?sec=4317|title=Hrvatski sabor - Grafi\u010dki standardi zastave RH|website=Sabor.hr|accessdate=9 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701053301/http://www.sabor.hr/Default.aspx?sec=4317|archive-date=1 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"60%\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px solid #aaaaaa; border-collapse: collapse; white-space: nowrap; text-align: left\"\n|- style=\"text-align: center; background: #eee\"\n! Scheme\n!style=\"background:#ff0000; color:white\"| Red\n!style=\"background:#ffffff; color:black\"| White\n!style=\"background:#0093dd; color:white\"| Cyan\n!style=\"background:#171796; color:white\"| Blue\n!style=\"background:#f7db17; color:black\"| Yellow\n!style=\"background:#000000; color:white\"| Black\n|-\n| [[Pantone]]\n| 186 C\n| Transparent white\n| Process Cyan C\n| Reflex Blue C\n| 108 C\n| Process Black C\n|-\n| [[CMYK color model|CMYK]]\n| 0-100-100-0\n| 0-0-0-0\n| 100-0-0-0\n| 100-82-0-2\n| 0-6-95-0\n| 0-0-0-100\n|-\n| [[RGB color model|RGB]]\n| 255-0-0\n| 255-255-255\n| 0-147-221\n| 23-23-150\n| 247-219-23\n| 0-0-0\n|-\n| [[Hexadecimal|Hex]]\n| #ff0000\n| #ffffff\n| #0093dd\n| #171796\n| #f7db17\n| #000000\n|}\n\n==Unicode==\nThe national flag of Croatia is represented as the [[Unicode]] [[emoji]] sequence {{unichar|1F1ED|REGIONAL INDICATOR SYMBOL LETTER H}} and {{unichar|1F1F7|REGIONAL INDICATOR SYMBOL LETTER R}}.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://emojipedia.org/flag-for-croatia/|title=\ud83c\udded\ud83c\uddf7 Flag for Croatia Emoji|access-date=2018-10-30}}</ref>\n\n==Historical flags==\n{{main|List of Croatian flags#Historical flags (tricolour)}}\n<gallery perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Flag of the Triune Kingdom of Croatia.svg|Flag of the [[Kingdom of Croatia (Habsburg)|Kingdom of Croatia]] since 1848. It was banned between 1852 to 1860<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeljko-heimer-fame.from.hr/hrvat/hr-hist.html|title=Hrvatska-povijesne zastave|website=zeljko-heimer-fame.from.hr|last=Heimer|first=\u017deljko|accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref>\nFile:Flag of the Kingdom of Croatia (Habsburg).svg|Flag of the Kingdom of Croatia (1852\u20131860)\nFile:Flag of the Kingdom of Slavonia.svg|Flag of the [[Kingdom of Slavonia]] (1852\u20131868)\nFile:Flag of the Kingdom of Dalmatia.svg|Flag of the [[Kingdom of Dalmatia]] (1820\u20131918)\nFile:Flag of Croatia-Slavonia.svg|Civil Flag of the [[Kingdom of Croatia-Slavonia]] (1868\u20131918)\nFile:Flag of the Triune Kingdom of Croatia.svg|Flag of the [[Triune Kingdom of Croatia, Slavonia and Dalmatia]] with the coat of arms, for usage in autonomic affairs. (1868\u20131918)<ref>Jelena Bor\u0161ak-Marijanovi\u0107, Zastave kroz stolje\u0107a, Croatian History Museum, Zagreb, 1996, p. 110</ref>\nFile:Flag_of_Banate_of_Croatia_(1939-1941).svg|Flag of the [[Banovina of Croatia]] (1939\u20131941)\nFile:Flag of Independent State of Croatia.svg|Flag of the [[Independent State of Croatia]] (1941\u20131945)\nFile:Flag_of_the_Federal_State_of_Croatia.svg|Flag of the [[Federal State of Croatia]] used by [[Yugoslav Partisans#Croatia|Croatian Partisans]] during [[World War II]], until 1945\nFile:Flag of SR Croatia.svg|Flag of the [[Socialist Republic of Croatia]] (1945\u20131990)\nFlag of Croatia (1990).svg| Variation of the flag of the Republic of Croatia (25 July \u2013 21 December 1990)\n</gallery>\n\n== Other official flags in Croatia ==\n<gallery perrow=\"6\">\n\nFile:Flag of the President of Croatia.svg|[[Flags of Croatia#Presidential|Standard of the President]] of the Republic of Croatia\n</gallery>\n\n=== Naval and other official flags===\n{{gallery|mode=nolines|whitebg=y|height=100\n|Naval Ensign of Croatia.svg|{{FIAV|normal}} Naval Ensign\n|Naval Jack of Croatia.svg|{{FIAV|normal}} Naval Jack\n\n|Flag of the President of Croatia.svg|{{FIAV|normal}} Flag of the President and the Commander-in-Chief\n|Naval flag defence minister (Croatia).gif|{{FIAV|normal}} Flag of the Minister of Defence\